<br>
“Calm down,” Lex said.  “Why are you in such a rush to get home anyway?”<br>
<br>
“I need to change,” she mumbled.  Lex glanced over at her.<br>
<br>
“Why?”<br>
<br>
“I just do, okay?”<br>
<br>
“Chloe, I sincerely doubt the outfit you’re wearing will make much of a difference when we tell your dad,” Lex said.<br>
<br>
‘It will if he sees the back of it,’ she thought.<br>
<br>
“I don’t see why that would ---?”  Lex trailed off as he pulled into the Sullivans’ driveway.  He tilted his head at her as the thought struck him.  “Something you’re not telling me?”<br>
<br>
“Let’s just get this over with,” she said and reached for her door handle.  Lex caught her arm before she could open the door.<br>
<br>
“Chloe, you weren’t – I mean, you weren’t a ---?”<br>
<br>
“Yes,” Chloe said through gritted teeth.  Lex leaned his head back against his seat and closed his eyes.<br>
<br>
‘God, I’m an ass,’ he thought.<br>
<br>
“No argument here,” Chloe said.  “Now can we hurry up and get inside so I can change before my dad sees my skirt?  Which you’re replacing by the way.”  She opened the door and Lex saw the back of her skirt as she started to climb out of the car.  His eyes grew wide and he quickly yanked her back inside the vehicle.<br>
<br>
“We can’t go in there,” he said.<br>
<br>
“That bad?”  She asked as she made a worried face.  He nodded.  Chloe sighed and stared at her house.  “We have to do this.  Maybe you could walk behind me or something.”<br>
<br>
“All the way to your room?  I think that might look a little suspicious.”<br>
<br>
“Well, we don’t have a lot of options do we?”  She asked in a slightly aggravated voice.  Lex took a deep breath.<br>
<br>
“You’re sure you want to do this?”  Lex asked.  “I could always call him again and say we got stranded again.”  Chloe spotted someone peeking out the blinds and shook her head.<br>
<br>
“It’s too late now, he’s seen us,” she said.  Lex followed her gaze to the blinds.<br>
<br>
“How can you be sure it was him?”<br>
<br>
‘I guess I can’t,’ Chloe admitted.  ‘I suppose it could be Lana.’<br>
<br>
“Great,” Lex mumbled sarcastically.<br>
<br>
“You don’t like Lana?”<br>
<br>
“Think about it Chloe.  Where Lana is, Clark inevitably follows,” Lex explained.  Chloe gave him a blank look and he squared his jaw.  ‘I really don’t feel like explaining why we didn’t go to the lab to him, do you?’  Chloe paled and shook her head.  “Good.  So, we’re leaving then?”  Chloe stopped his hand before he turned the keys.<br>
<br>
“We can’t leave.”<br>
<br>
“Chloe ---”<br>
<br>
“Fine!  I’ll stay and you can leave,” she said.  ‘Just like always,’ she thought.  Lex turned to face her.<br>
<br>
“I beg your pardon?  When have I ever left you?”<br>
<br>
“I wasn’t talking about you in particular,” she said and opened the car door again, managing to get out before Lex could stop her.  <br>
<br>
‘Damn it.’<br>
<br>
‘Just leave,’ she thought as she started walking up to her front door.  Lex swiftly jumped out of his car and draped his overcoat on Chloe’s shoulders.  She looked at him quizzically.<br>
<br>
“It’s longer than yours,” he explained.  They walked up to the door and Chloe opened it hesitantly.  Lana came in from the living room and smiled at Chloe.<br>
<br>
“It took you long enough, you were out in the car for-,” she trailed off when she saw that Lex had followed Chloe into the house, and that Chloe was wearing Lex’s overcoat over her own jacket.  Her eyes darted questioningly at Chloe who shot her a nervous smile and grabbed her arm.<br>
<br>
“Think you can keep my dad distracted long enough for me to change?”  Chloe asked hopefully.  Lana furrowed her brow in confusion.  “I *started* early and Lex was kind enough to lend me his jacket to cover up,” Chloe lied.  Lana’s eyes grew wide and her mouth dropped open a little.<br>
<br>
“Oh!  Oh, of course,” Lana said, practically pushing Chloe toward the stairs.  Chloe ran up the stairs and Lana turned around to face Lex with an uncomfortable look on her face.  Lana’s tension eased when she saw that Lex wasn’t even paying attention to her, but only following Chloe with his eyes.  “I’m sure she’ll pay for dry cleaning.”  Lex turned his head to look at her and shot her a confused expression.  “Your coat, you know, if blood gets on it,” she explained while wringing her hands.  Lex gave her a curt nod.<br>
<br>
“I’m not worried about the coat Lana,” he said with a small grin.  “Where is Gabe?”  <br>
<br>
“On the phone with Clark,” Lana said with a partial eye roll.  Lex arched an eyebrow, but Lana didn’t elaborate.  Her face had marred into a distinct look of agitation and Lex tilted his head at her.<br>
<br>
“You seem upset,” he observed.<br>
<br>
“It’s nothing,” she lied.<br>
<br>
‘Lana’s upset?’  Chloe thought.<br>
<br>
‘Apparently.’<br>
<br>
‘Why?’<br>
<br>
‘I’m trying to find out.  She mentioned Clark being on the phone with your dad and then her mood changed.’<br>
<br>
‘Huh.  I thought they were getting better at the whole *let’s just be friends* thing.’<br>
<br>
‘I’m sure the fact that you ---’<br>
<br>
‘Don’t even think it Luthor.  I have nothing to do with their ongoing soap opera problems.’<br>
<br>
‘Of course not *sweetheart*,’ Lex thought sarcastically.  “Lana, this wouldn’t have anything to do with Clark would it?”  Lana looked down at the floor and then back up to him.<br>
<br>
“I,” she started, but then paused as if she couldn’t find the right words to say.  “Do you think Clark still likes Chloe?”  Lex pumped his hands into fists and then released them.<br>
<br>
‘She just asked me if I thought if Clark still liked you,’ Lex thought.<br>
<br>
‘So tell her the truth.  Clark never liked me,’ Chloe thought bitterly.<br>
<br>
‘That’s not the truth.’<br>
<br>
‘Yes it is.’<br>
<br>
‘No it’s not.’<br>
<br>
“Lex?”  Lana asked, snapping him out of his mental argument with Chloe.<br>
<br>
“I think you and I might be in the same situation,” he responded without apologizing for spacing out.  Lana crinkled her brow.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean?”<br>
<br>
‘Yes, what *do* you mean Lex?’  Chloe thought.<br>
<br>
“You like Clark,” Lex said.<br>
<br>
“He’s my friend.”<br>
<br>
