<br>
“The purpose of dinner is to actually *eat* the food in front of you,” he teased. <br>
<br>
“Sorry.  My mind is somewhere else tonight,” she said.<br>
<br>
“You’re worried about Chloe,” he observed.  Lana paled, wondering how much Chloe’s dad actually knew about what was going on.<br>
<br>
“I ---”<br>
<br>
“Lana, if there’s one thing I know about my daughter, it’s that she’s a big girl.  And in most cases she can take care of herself.  I’m sure she’s just trying to brainstorm a way to write about what’s happened to her --- and driving Lex completely out of his mind.”  He said the last part with a smile and Lana forced a grin onto her lips.<br>
<br>
‘Either that or they’re --- it’s a good thing Mr. Sullivan can’t read my mind,’ Lana thought.  <br>
<br>
The phone rang, snapping Lana out of her thoughts, and she practically jumped out of her chair to get it.  Gabe shook his head lightly in amusement.<br>
<br>
‘Teenagers,’ he thought.<br>
<br>
“Hello?  Sullivan residence,” Lana answered.<br>
<br>
“Lana – it’s Clark,” Clark said hurriedly.  Lana’s face fell and she turned away so Gabe couldn’t see the worried expression that she was sure now commanded her facial features.<br>
<br>
“What happened?”  She asked in a quieter voice.  “Did you get there in time?”  Lana cast a weary glance in Gabe’s direction, but he was thankfully concentrating on the food in front of him.<br>
<br>
“Chloe – she stopped breathing.  Mouth to mouth didn’t work.  The paramedics were able to get her heart beating again, but ---”<br>
<br>
“What?!”  Lana asked in panic.  Gabe’s head turned quickly in Lana’s direction and he looked at her questioningly.<br>
<br>
“She’s at the hospital now, but she hasn’t woken up.”  Clark paused and Lana could practically see the apprehensive look on his face.  “Lex says he can’t hear her,” Clark said somberly.  Lana suddenly felt ill and the phone dropped from her hand.  Gabe got up from his chair and put a steadying arm around her back as she tried to sink down to the floor herself.  He moved her to the chair and she sat down.  “Lana?  Are you still there?”  Gabe picked up the phone.<br>
<br>
“Hello?”<br>
<br>
Clark cringed when he heard Gabe’s voice come through the receiver.<br>
<br>
“Hey – hi – it’s Clark,” the young man stammered.  He took a deep breath and then released the words he needed to say in a rushed blur.  “Chloe’s in the hospital.”<br>
<br>
“What?  How did this happen?”<br>
<br>
“I don’t know.  We were talking and she just --- collapsed.  Then she stopped breathing.  They had to use those electric paddle things to get her heart started again, and ---” Clark rambled emotionally and Gabe now knew the reason Lana had almost fainted.  <br>
<br>
“Clark?”  Gabe asked, cutting the boy off.  “Where is she now?”<br>
<br>
“The hospital.  They’re running tests.  Lex thinks it might have something to do with that chemical that they were exposed to.”<br>
<br>
“Okay,” Gabe said with a calm he didn’t possess.  “We’re leaving now.  We’ll meet you there.”  He hung up the phone without saying goodbye and then grabbed his keys off the key holder.  Lana stood up and followed him out to the car in a complete daze. <br>
<br>
She couldn’t believe this was happening.  She mentally berated herself for being so concerned about what Chloe and Lex might have been doing when it seemed so trivial now.  From what Clark had said; Chloe had technically died.  When a person stops breathing and their heart stops beating – that’s death.  Lana wrapped her arms around herself for the duration of the ride to the hospital.  Not only had Chloe died and been revived, but now she wasn’t waking up, and Lex couldn’t hear her in his head.  She wasn’t sure why that last part bothered her so much, but it did.  Because it meant that although Chloe’s body was still there, that Chloe might not be.<br>
<br>
Clark watched them come in through the emergency entrance and he walked over to them.  He and Lana hugged, but it was obvious it was just for mutual comfort.<br>
<br>
“Any news?”  Gabe asked.  Clark shoved his hands in his pockets and shook his head.<br>
<br>
“They need to get your permission to send some of Chloe’s blood out for additional testing in Metropolis, but she hasn’t woken up yet,” Clark said.  His eyes briefly lit up.  “Oh!  But she’s breathing on her own now, so the doctors are optimistic.”  Gabe paled.  He didn’t realize there had been a point where his daughter hadn’t been breathing on her own past the initial moment of collapsing.  <br>
<br>
“Can we see her?”  Lana asked.  Clark looked uneasy and Lana looked at him questioningly.<br>
<br>
“They wouldn’t let me or Lex in to see her,” he said and then looked at Gabe, “but you’re family, so they might let you in.”  Gabe nodded once and then left Clark and Lana alone while he went to talk to someone behind the admissions desk.<br>
<br>
“It’s bad, isn’t it?”  Lana asked quietly.  <br>
<br>
“Yeah.”<br>
<br>
“Do you really think it has something to do with the chemical they were exposed to?”  <br>
<br>
“I don’t know,” Clark said.  “Maybe.  But it seems like if that was the case, then Lex would be sick too.”  <br>
<br>
Lana looked at the floor and fidgeted with her hands.  <br>
<br>
“Did you – I mean, did they ---?”  She trailed off and looked imploringly at Clark, hoping he would know what she was talking about.  She felt bad for even bringing it up, but if they had then there was a chance that it might have something to do with why Chloe was sick.  ‘Okay, that’s reaching,’ she thought.  But stranger things had certainly happened in Smallville.  Clark blushed and ducked his head.<br>
<br>
“I – um – don’t know for sure,” he said.  &quot;When I got there, they were kissing and ---” Clark paused while he ran his hand around the back of his neck.<br>
<br>
“And?”<br>
<br>
“And Lex didn’t have a shirt on,” he said in a hushed voice.<br>
<br>
“Oh.”  Lana crinkled up her nose and caught Clark’s eyes with her own.  “Well, that doesn’t mean anything.  Maybe you got there just in time.”  Her tone was entirely too hopeful and Clark couldn’t bear to tell her that the heavy musky smell that had been in Lex’s bedroom would suggest otherwise.<br>
<br>
“Maybe,” he said, forcing a fake half-smile onto his lips.  <br>
<br>
Gabe came back over to them and motioned to the hallway that led to the elevators.<br>
<br>
“They’ll let us in now, but only for a little while,” he said.  Lana looked relieved and Clark looked worried.<br>
<br>
“What about Lex?”  He asked.  Gabe glanced around the ER’s waiting area.<br>
<br>
“Where is he?”<br>
<br>
“He went to get coffee,” Clark said and then smiled when Lex came back through the doors he had seen him leave through.  Lex walked over to them with a cup-holder holding four coffees.  Gabe arched an eyebrow and Lex curled up one corner of his mouth in a sad grin.<br>
<br>
“I figured you and Lana would get here while it was still hot,” Lex explained.  Gabe grinned gratefully at him.<br>
<br>
“They’re going to let us in to see her,” Clark said, interrupting the silence that settled upon the group as each person took a coffee from the holder.  Lex gave him a somewhat blank stare in disbelief.  <br>
<br>
Why hadn’t Clark just told him that the second he came over?  Lex turned on his heel and started walking toward the elevators without waiting for the rest of them.  Clark turned to Gabe, who seemed surprised by Lex’s actions.<br>
<br>
“He’s been --- worried,” Clark explained.  ‘Obsessive, angry, crazy,’ he immediately added inwardly.  Gabe nodded and the three of them set off for the elevators as well.<br>
<br>
They reached Chloe’s room and Lex winced when he saw her hooked up to the machines.  He still couldn’t hear her voice in his head, and tried to make himself believe that there was a possibility that Clark was right about the chemical reaction wearing off, but it didn’t work.  Gabe started talking to her, convinced by the doctors that Chloe could somehow hear him in her comatose state.  Clark went next and uttered a string of apologies that Lex just wanted to kill him for.  And then it was Lana’s turn.  The poor girl actually had tears in her eyes as she sat down in the chair next to Chloe’s bed.<br>
<br>
“You can’t leave, Chloe,” she said with overwrought emotion.  “Everyone always leaves me.  My parents, Whitney --- I can’t lose you too.  Please wake up.”  Gabe and Clark seemed sympathetic to Lana’s speech, but Lex suddenly heard a familiar voice in his head.<br>
<br>
‘Oh, God.  Shut up, shut up, shut up!’  Chloe thought.  ‘They didn’t *leave* you!  They died!  There’s a difference!’<br>
<br>
Lex couldn’t help himself.  A broad smile spread across his lips and he started laughing loudly – partially because of what Chloe had thought and partially out of relief that he could hear her again.  Lana, Clark, and Gabe all gave him strange and almost horrified looks.  He managed to pull himself together enough to talk to her.<br>
<br>
‘God!  Don’t ever do that to me again, Chloe,’ he thought warningly.<br>
<br>
‘Why?  You have a nice laugh,’ she thought.<br>
<br>
‘That’s not what I meant and you know it.’<br>
<br>
‘Prove it,’ she thought teasingly.  He chuckled again and Clark, Lana, and Gabe continued to stare at him.<br>
<br>
‘You’re getting me in trouble, Sullivan.’<br>
<br>
‘It’s not my fault you have a good sense of humor,’ she countered.  Lex grinned.<br>
<br>
‘You’re only saying that because it’s the same as yours.’<br>
<br>
‘Yep.’<br>
<br>
‘But I meant what I said,’ he thought.<br>
<br>
‘Lex ---’ <br>
<br>
‘I was scared,’ he admitted.  ‘And Luthors don’t get scared.’<br>
<br>
‘I’m not sure what to say.’<br>
<br>
‘You don’t have to say anything,’ he thought.  ‘Chloe, there’s something you should know.  I think I lo---’<br>
<br>
Lex was so engaged in his inner conversation with Chloe that it took him a minute before he realized that Clark had been trying to get his attention.<br>
<br>
“You can hear her again, can’t you?”  Clark asked hopefully, cutting off Lex’s thoughts.  Lex nodded and Clark gave him a lopsided grin.  “I don’t suppose you could tell her to wake up?”<br>
<br>
‘I don’t suppose you could tell him to go away so I can take a nap in peace?’  <br>
<br>
‘Tell him yourself.’<br>
<br>
‘Spoilsport.’  Chloe’s eyes started to flutter open and Lana gave her a smothering hug.  ‘Air – need – air.’  Lex chuckled and watched as Gabe and Clark gave her hugs as well, only barely restraining the growl he felt from coming out when Clark hugged her.  Chloe smiled weakly at them.  “Hey,” she said in a raspy and whispered voice.<br>
<br>
One of the doctors chose that precise moment to walk into the room, surprised by the amount of people surrounding the patient, and even more surprised that Chloe was now awake.  <br>
<br>
“How are you feeling?”  He finally managed to ask.<br>
<br>
“Okay.”<br>
<br>
‘Really?’  Lex asked.<br>
<br>
‘No, but I’m not telling him that.  He’ll want to keep me here longer.’<br>
<br>
‘He’ll want to do that anyway.’<br>
<br>
The doctor glanced at the paperwork on the clipboard in front of him and a small, concerned frown graced his lips.  He looked at her visitors.<br>
<br>
“I need to talk to Chloe alone, so if you all ---”<br>
<br>
‘The hell you do,’ Lex thought, shooting daggers at the man with his eyes.<br>
<br>
‘Calm down.  He’s just the doctor.’<br>
<br>
‘But ---’<br>
<br>
Chloe smiled warmly at him and Lex’s resolve melted away.  He nodded once.<br>
<br>
“We’ll be in the hall,” he said.<br>
<br>
“There’s a waiting area just a few doors down,” the doctor said.  “I’m sure it will be more comfortable.”  Lex squared his jaw.<br>
<br>
‘Tell me again why I shouldn’t kill him?’<br>
<br>
The doctor, oblivious to Chloe and Lex’s inner conversations, grinned at her visitors.  Clark tugged on Lex’s arm to get him to leave the room and the doctor could have sworn he heard an animalistic growl come reverberate from Lex’s throat.  After they left, the doctor shut the door and took a breath before making eye contact with Chloe.<br>
<br>
“Something came up on your blood work with the tests we ran here, but I suspect you already knew that,” he said.  Chloe barely nodded.  <br>
<br>
‘Great.  The stupid chemical is in my blood and they’re going to ship me off to a government facility to determine if I’m an alien,’ she thought.<br>
<br>
‘What?’<br>
<br>
‘Not really.  At least I hope not.’  Chloe forced herself to concentrate on the doctor as he continued to speak.<br>
<br>
“Chloe, I know that it must have been hard to accept the results, but I hope you know that no matter what else is going on, there are options.”<br>
<br>
‘What the hell is he talking about?’  She thought.<br>
<br>
“There’s always adoption, or even abortion if ---”<br>
<br>
“What?!”<br>
<br>
The doctor gave her a strange look and Chloe shook her head.<br>
<br>
“I think you guys mixed up my results with someone else’s,” she said.  The doctor looked through the paperwork again and then shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Chloe Sullivan,” he read.  “High HCG levels accompanied by an unknown substance presumed to be a toxin.”  Chloe’s eyes widened.<br>
<br>
“But ---”<br>
<br>
“Listen, your near experience with death may have been enough to make you reevaluate things, but I’m not willing to take chances on your life or your baby’s, so I’m putting you on suicide watch for the next forty-eight hours.”<br>
<br>
Chloe’s mouth dropped open and the doctor turned around to leave the room.<br>
<br>
“This isn’t happening, this isn’t happening,” she repeated to herself in a mantra-like form.<br>
<br>
